\subsection{Data Format}
Each entry encapsulates the dialogue as an array of turns, accompanied by the target summary. During inference, we explicitly preserve the speaker tags (e.g., \textit{Patient:, Health Worker:}) to ensure the model accurately attributes clinical statements to the correct individual.

\section{Models and Hardware Constraints}
Deploying AI in clinical settings necessitates strict adherence to data privacy regulations. Because patient transcripts contain Protected Health Information (PHI), relying on external, proprietary cloud APIs is often prohibited. To ensure our findings are ecologically valid for real-world, on-premise hospital IT infrastructure, we constrain our experiments to hardware equivalent to a single legacy enterprise GPU (NVIDIA V100, 32GB VRAM). Consequently, we evaluate two 7-billion parameter (7B) open-weights models.

\subsection{Mistral-7B-Instruct}
Mistral-7B is a highly optimized transformer developed by Mistral AI, employing Grouped Query Attention (GQA) for efficient inference and Sliding Window Attention (SWA). Despite its compact parameter count, it demonstrates competitive reasoning capabilities. We utilize the instruction-tuned variant (v0.2) as our baseline for complex formatting and instruction adherence.

\subsection{Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct}
Qwen2.5-7B is trained on a substantially larger and more diverse multilingual corpus compared to many Western-centric LLMs. Its pre-training data provides enhanced coverage of Asian languages, making it a strong candidate for cross-lingual clinical summarization, particularly for the Dravidian and Indo-Aryan languages underrepresented in standard models.

\section{Methodology}
We systematically evaluate four distinct experimental paradigms for cross-lingual clinical dialogue summarization. Our core objective is generating a structured English clinical note from a source Indic dialogue.

\subsection{Zero-Shot Prompting}
Zero-shot prompting evaluates the inherent multilingual capability of each model without task-specific demonstrations. A system prompt instructs the model to act as a clinical assistant, generating a concise summary from the dialogue covering chief complaints, assessments, and recommended treatments. No in-context examples are provided.

\subsection{Few-Shot Prompting}
Few-shot prompting augments the prompt with $k=3$ demonstration examples drawn from the training set. We employ a bilingual demonstration strategy, exposing the model to the desired structural English output while referencing native-language inputs. To manage the context window, lengthy dialogues are truncated from the middle, preserving the opening context (symptoms) and closing discussion (treatments), which carry the highest density of clinical entities.

\subsection{Translation-Augmented Inference (TTS)}
A well-established strategy for low-resource NLP is the translate-then-process cascade. We explore whether routing non-English dialogues through a high-quality Neural Machine Translation (NMT) system before summarization yields improvements over direct multilingual inference. 

We utilize \textbf{IndicTrans2}, a state-of-the-art NMT model developed specifically for Indian languages. The pipeline operates as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Non-English dialogues are translated to English via IndicTrans2.
    \item The translated English dialogue is passed to the LLM (Mistral/Qwen) using the zero-shot prompt.
    \item The LLM generates the final English clinical summary.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT)}
To adapt the pre-trained models directly to the domain without exceeding our 32GB VRAM limit, we employ Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) via Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA). Training is conducted on paired Indic-to-English examples to internalize stylistic and structural clinical norms (Table \ref{tab:hyperparams}).

