\section{Evaluation Framework}
We employ a three-tier framework to assess surface-level text similarity, strict clinical entity fidelity, and holistic safety.

\subsection{Tier 1: Automated Text Similarity Metrics}
We compute ROUGE (1, 2, L) for structural n-gram overlap and BERTScore for contextual token-embedding similarity. While BERTScore is robust to lexical variation and paraphrase, achieving high semantic overlap does not guarantee clinical factuality. An LLM may accurately capture conversational flow while simultaneously hallucinating a critical medication.

\subsection{Tier 2: Clinical Entity-Level Analysis (NER)}
To measure clinical accuracy, we perform a fine-grained analysis of entity coverage across five categories: \textit{Symptoms, Diagnoses/Conditions, Substances/Habits, Procedures/Tests,} and \textit{Treatments.}

\subsubsection{Master Ground Truth Extraction}
To prevent translation artifacts from skewing evaluation across 10 languages, entities are extracted from the original English gold dialogues using Azure OpenAI's GPT-5 deployment. This yields a canonical ``Master English Ground Truth'' for each of the 60 parallel scenarios.

\subsubsection{Matching and Metrics}
Generated summaries undergo the same GPT-5 extraction. We then compare the generated entities against the gold entities. Notably, we abandoned programmatic fuzzy string matching (e.g., Gestalt pattern matching) because it falsely penalized models for valid clinical synonyms (e.g., ``hydration'' vs. ``stay hydrated'') and hierarchical abstractions. 

Instead, we utilize an \textbf{LLM-as-a-Judge semantic mapping protocol}. The judge determines True Positives (TP), False Positives (FP), and False Negatives (FN). From these, we compute:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Precision:} $TP / (TP + FP)$ (Anti-Hallucination)
    \item \textbf{Recall:} $TP / (TP + FN)$ (Anti-Omission)
    \item \textbf{F1 Score:} Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall.
    \item \textbf{Hallucination Rate:} $FP / (TP + FP)$
    \item \textbf{Omission Rate:} $FN / (TP + FN)$
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Tier 3: LLM-as-a-Judge Quality Assessment}
Finally, we employ a structured LLM judge to assess holistic quality dimensions critical to clinical settings (Table \ref{tab:quality_dim}). Each dimension is scored on a Likert scale (1–5) based on an explicit scoring rubric.

